source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/quick-creamy-penne-5971296ed56afa30476ea6a2
course: main course
time required: 25 minutes
servings: 2
---

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{}ed water to a boil. Pick
@mint{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; discard stems. Roughly chop leaves. Mince or
grate @garlic{2%cloves}.

Heat a large, empty #pan{} over medium-low heat. Add @pine nuts{1%ounce} and
toast, tossing frequently, until lightly browned and fragrant, ~{2-3%minutes}.
Remove from pan and set aside.

Once water is boiling, add @penne pasta{6%ounce} to #pot{}. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until just shy of al dente, about ~{7%minutes}. Add @peas{4%ounce}
to pot and continue cooking until peas are tender and penne is al dente,
~{2-3%minutes} more. Carefully scoop out and reserve 1/2 cup pasta cooking
water, then drain.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in pan used for pine nuts over medium
heat. Add garlic and cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}.

Stir penne, peas, @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit},
half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, and 1/4 cup pasta cooking water into pan.
Gently toss over medium heat until a thick, creamy sauce forms, ~{3-4%minutes}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: Add another splash or two of pasta cooking water if sauce seems dry.

Divide penne mixture between plates. Sprinkle with mint (to taste),
pine nuts, and remaining Parmesan.

> The simplest way to create a meal that's fast and easy but still tasty is by
> focusing on a few thoughtfully paired powerhouse ingredients. In this case,
> that's mint for fresh herbiness, peas for a touch of sweet green, and pine
> nuts for a hint of buttery flavor and crunch. When tossed into this quick,
> creamy pasta, they create contrasts and combos that feel new with each bite.